Premiums for claims made against people driving vehicles not primarily designed for use on the road were set to rise under the contentious law. The legislation includes all vehicles that are generally exempt from needing motor insurance, such as mobility scooters, golf buggies and heavy-duty lawnmowers.   The EU law would have seen British drivers’ insurance premiums rise by around £50 a year if it was implemented in the UK. On Twitter, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps announced on Friday: "Delighted to report Lord Robathan – working with Govt – has taken us a step closer to remove an EU requirement that if implemented would have increased motorists’ insurance premiums by c.£50 a year. The Bill passed Lords Second Reading today! #VNUK #BrexitDividend." FOLLOW BELOW FOR LIVE UPDATES ON BREXIT…